This isn't just an article; it's a footnote to a policy, a whispered explanation of why certain doors remain shut. It’s an [explanatory essay](/Wikipedia:Project_namespace), mind you, not gospel. It elaborates on the [Open proxies](/Wikipedia:PROXY) policy, offering context that the policy itself, in its stark pronouncements, might omit. Think of it as the backstory to why some connections are deemed… inconvenient. This particular piece isn’t one of those ironclad [Wikipedia's policies or guidelines](/Wikipedia:Policies_and_guidelines), no. It hasn't undergone the full gauntlet of community scrutiny, that rigorous [thoroughly vetted by the community](/Wikipedia:PROPOSAL) process. It’s more of an informed opinion, a reasoned argument.

### WP:TOR

You might see it abbreviated as [WP:TOR](/Wikipedia:TOR). Some call it that. Others might confuse it with [WikiProject Toronto](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Toronto), which is a rather dull thought, if you ask me. This essay, however, is about [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)), that intricate network designed for anonymity and, crucially, for bypassing censorship. It’s a tool, yes, but one that’s become a double-edged sword on Wikipedia. The sheer volume of abuse from [vandals](/Wikipedia:Vandalism) has led to a rather blunt solution: [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) exit nodes are, for the most part, barred from contributing. If you’re using [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) to edit Wikipedia, you’ll find yourself needing [IP block exemption](/Wikipedia:IPBE). Reading, however? That’s a different story. No restrictions there.

It’s important, the essay argues, to approach [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) users with [good faith](/Wikipedia:AGF). And I agree. There are legitimate, even vital, reasons for seeking anonymity online. In nations where [Wikipedia is censored](/Censorship_of_Wikipedia) or outright blocked, [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) becomes not just a convenience, but a lifeline to information. And in this age of pervasive [governmental surveillance programs](/List_of_government_surveillance_projects), the desire to exercise one's [right to anonymity](/Wikipedia:Wikipedia_is_anonymous) is hardly a radical concept. It’s a quiet assertion of privacy, a basic human right, or so I’ve heard.

#### Technical Details

The [policy on open proxies](/Wikipedia:Open_proxies) is quite clear, and rather unforgiving: open proxies can be blocked, indefinitely, at any time. The software, a thing called MediaWiki, has an extension – [TorBlock](/mw:Extension:TorBlock) – that handles this automatically. It’s a digital bouncer, effectively. Unless an account has been granted that coveted [IP block exemption](/Wikipedia:IPBE), editing through [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) is a non-starter. The English Wikipedia, in particular, seems to have taken a rather dim view of [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) abuse. They’ve gone as far as to block entire [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) exit nodes, which means no new accounts, no edits, unless you’ve got that special exemption.

#### IP Block Exemption

So, you’re a registered user, you haven’t caused any trouble, and you need to edit from behind [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network))? You can petition for [IP block exemption](/Wikipedia:IPBE), or [IP block exemption](/Wikipedia:IPECPROXY) as it’s also known. This allows your logged-in self to bypass those blanket IP blocks. The instructions for requesting this are, apparently, laid out somewhere. [These instructions](/Wikipedia:IPECPROXY). However, and this is where it gets tedious, proving your "good standing" while simultaneously maintaining your anonymity—which requires *not* using [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) for your established edits—is a bit of a Catch-22, isn't it? A paradox wrapped in a security measure.

#### Closed Proxy

For those navigating the Great Firewall, a dedicated group of editors has established a network of [closed proxy](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_on_closed_proxies) servers. It’s a niche solution for a specific problem, allowing access for editors who would otherwise be completely cut off. If you find yourself in that particular predicament, the [WikiProject on closed proxies](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_on_closed_proxies) is where you’ll find the details.

#### Alternative Proxies

While [Tor](/Tor_(anonymity_network)) is the poster child for anonymity networks and the one systematically blocked on Wikipedia, it’s not the only game in town. Other anonymizing proxies exist. Many might also find themselves blocked, but not all. Some might only be [soft-blocked](/Wikipedia:Blocking_policy), meaning you might still be able to create an account, which is a start, I suppose.

#### Need an account and can't create one?

If you’re in that unfortunate position, needing an account but unable to create one due to proxy restrictions, the advice is simple: follow the same bureaucratic labyrinth outlined in the § IP block exemption section. It’s the same process, the same hoops to jump through.

